USAGE
To use the code, simply run ann.py with cmd or terminal
with both the .xlsx or .csv file in the same directory as the .py file:

    > python ann.py

The program will start and looks something like this:

       ann.py   
      \         
     --o--o-->  
      /         
    
    Python Program for for Artificial Neural Network Modelling
    Enter the csv or xlsx file for Data Training : 
    Enter the csv or xlsx file for Data Testing  : 

and enter the file name and extension in each entry, 
e.g. data_training.xlsx and data_testing.xlsx  or 
     data_training.csv and data_testing.csv
Now remember that the training data and testing data should have the same 
numbers and descriptions of columns, otherwise it the code will not work.

For dataset example, see the provided files:
data_training.xlsx and data_testing.xlsx

Next, the program will display the first column of your datasets, which is the 
header of your input and output data. It should looks something like this:

    Loading data_training.xlsx and data_testing.xlsx.
    
    +-----------------+-------+
    |   Column Name   | Index |
    +-----------------+-------+
    |     No. ..      |   1   |
    |  H2O Molar ..   |   2   |
    |  SO2 Molar ..   |   3   |
    |  I2 Molar  ..   |   4   |
    |  H2 Produc ..   |   5   |
    |  Cycle Eff ..   |   6   |
    |  He Temper ..   |   7   |
    +-----------------+-------+

The program ask you to input the indexes of columns that you want to set 
as input and output.

    Please select the INPUT column Index(s) (separated with comma)             : 

The user should input the number of Index of the corresponding Column Name. 
For example, if you want to set Columns H2O Molar .., SO2 Molar .., and 
I2 Molar  .. as the INPUT, you should put 2,3,4 in the input.

    Please select the OUTPUT column Index(s) (separated with comma)            : 

The same goes for the next bit. For example, if you want to set Columns 
H2 Produc .. and Cycle Eff .. as the OUTPUT, you should put 5,6 in the input.

The program then ask you to input several ANN parameters. First, the user is 
asked to enter the number of hidden layers. 

    Please enter the number of hidden layers (1 ~ ∞)                           : 

The next is the number of uniform neuron per hidden layer. 

    Please enter the number of uniform neurons per hidden layer (1 ~ ∞)        : 

The term "uniform" in this context means that every hidden layer will have the 
same number of neurons. For a customized number of neurons per hidden layer the 
user can input custom in the input like so:

    Please enter the number of uniform neurons per hidden layer (1 ~ ∞)        : custom

If that is the case, then the program will ask the number of neurons in each of 
the hidden layers, separated with comma, like in the input and ouput.

    Please enter the number of neurons per hidden layer (separated with comma) :

Remember that this entry must match the number of hidden layers in the previous 
entry. Suppose you entered 3 as a value for hidden layers and you entered custom
as number of neurons, then you can enter a,b,c where the a, b, and c are the 
number of neurons in each of the hidden layer, e.g. 5,11,4 (or any of the 
possitive integer you like).

The last one is the number of training cycles.

    Please enter the number of training cycles (1 ~ ∞)                         : 

The range of these inputs are 1 through ∞ or possitive integer value. 
After that, the program reiterates user's input

The program will train, test, and evaluate the neural network model. The epochs 
and loss value of training, weights and biases of neurons, the evaluated RMSE, 
relative error, and squared error, as well as the Coefficient of Determinations 
(R^2) of each output and overall can be seen in the terminal. 

The ANN model implemented in this program uses the ReLU activation function. 
It will print out the equations of the predicted output with ReLU function 
f(z) = max(0,z). The ReLU function works on MATLAB code, spreadsheet 
applications (Ms.Excel, LibreOffice Calc, OpenOffice, etc.), and many 
other mathematical inqueries.

The program then shows the ANN Architecture diagram, the Model Loss graph, the 
Error Histogram, and the Training States graph. The Actual vs Predicted Value 
graph along with their R^2 value, are shown, with the number depends on the 
output specified by user. These graphs are shown in a separate matplotlib 
window and saved to the directory as several .png files, ready for publications 
or data visualization purposes.

The model from ANN training is also saved as ann_model.keras. This .keras file 
can be further reviewed with scikit-learn, tensorflow, and keras libraries.

The basic outputs from this ANN Modelling is then exported to ann.out file. The 
ann.out is just a text file containing ANN parameters, results, and evaluations.
If user experienced any formatting difficulty, the user can just highlight the 
output from the cmd or terminal and copy-paste it to a blank text file. That 
way, the user can assess the step-by-step of ANN more comprehensively.

Background:
This is by no means a novel Python code for modelling artificial neural network.
Author is sure that there are dedicated library or more advanced code out there 
for this purpose. It started out as a research capacity on Neural Network and 
it just make sense to implement the coding knowledge. The Author hope that this 
would help. 

